JOHANNESBURG KPMG's former Chief Executive Officer, Moses Kgosana, resigned from his position at Alexander Forbes with immediate effect on Monday. Kgosana, who was a non-executive director at Alexander Forbes, was due to take up the role of chairman from August 31 at the financial and risk services provider, but withdrew from the role.It comes after Kgosana was exposed last week in the #GuptaLeaks as having had a close relationship with Atul Gupta during the time when KPMG was the auditors and advisors to the Oakbay Group entities owned by the Gupta family.READ: #GuptaLeaks: The Dubai Laundromat - How millions from dairy paid for Sun City weddingAccording to investigative journalism unit AmaBhungane, the Guptas allegedly laundered money in the region of R30-million earmarked for the Free State Dairy project through their company, Linkway Trading (Pty) Ltd, and KPMG allowed them to use the money to pay for the lavish 2013 wedding of a family member, writing it off as a business expense. KPMG denied wrongdoing.READ: KPMG denies involvement in Gupta wedding scandal Since becoming aware of recently published allegations in respect of KPMG, which related to his (Kgosana's) previous position as chief executive officer and senior partner of KPMG, he believes it is the correct course of action for himself, the company, its clients and shareholders, Alexander Forbes said in a statement. Mr Kgosana felt that the demands on his time in the role of chairman of the company whilst attending to these allegations, will interfere with his deliverable expectations. Alexander Forbes welcomes this decisive action. Alexander Forbes said the current chairman, Sello Moloko, would remain non-executive chairman in the interim and thanked Kgosana for his contribution as a director over the past two years.African News Agency